text:
Quick and easy cinnamon roll bites-the perfect way to satisfy a cinnamon roll craving! 

- Hi everyone, I‚Äôm editing the caption to include the recipe for you all. As far as bake time is concerned, these are very small bite sized pieces so they don‚Äôt need much time to cook through. I‚Äôve made the adjustments to the timing but you can bake for a few more minutes if necessary. Please don‚Äôt over bake. 

For the dough:
1 cup (130 g) all purpose flour
1 tsp baking powder
1/4 tsp salt
1/3 cup + 2 tsp (90 ml) milk or water (if using milk, microwave for a few seconds so that it's not cold)
1/2 tsp vanilla

The coating
1 tbsp (14 g) unsalted butter ‚Äì melted and cooled to room temp
3 tbsp granulated sugar
1-2 tsp ground cinnamon

For the glaze:
2 tbsp powdered sugar
1/2-1 tsp milk
1/4 tsp vanilla

INSTRUCTIONS
- Preheat the oven to 375‚Ñâ (190‚ÑÉ) and line a loaf pan with parchment paper or lightly grease it with butter.
- In a mixing bowl, add the flour, salt, and baking powder and whisk to combine.
- Mix the milk and vanilla in a cup and then pour into the flour mixture. 
- Combine to form a soft and smooth dough ball, transfer to a lightly floured work surface and roll it to form a log (about 10 inches long).
- Press down on it slightly to flatten it out to about 2 inches wide, and then cut it into 10 pieces. Then cut each piece in half for a total of 20 bite sized pieces.
- Place the dough pieces in a bowl, pour the melted butter over them and gently toss so that each piece is coated in butter.
- In a separate bowl, mix the cinnamon and sugar together and then pour it over the buttered pieces of dough. Toss again, making sure that every piece is covered in cinnamon sugar.
- Transfer to the prepared loaf pan, make sure they lay flat and are not stacked on top of each other, and bake for 9-10 minutes. (These cook through fairly quickly but you can bake for a few more minutes, if necessary. Just be careful not to over bake) 
- While that bakes, make the glaze by mixing together the powdered sugar, milk, and vanilla. Taste and adjust to your desired sweetness and consistency.
- When the cinnamon roll bites are ready, let them cool for just a few minutes and then drizzle with the glaze. Enjoy warm!

You can also find the recipe on 

https://flavorednice.com/cinnamon-roll-bites/.

Crumbl released their Dubai Chocolate Brownie, but why buy it when you can make an even better one at home? ü§é‚ú®

Ingredients
üü§Brownie Base
* 180g caster sugar
* 2 eggs
* 113g unsalted butter (for browning)
* 170g chopped chocolate
* 80g plain flour
* 3 tbsp cocoa powder
* ¬Ω tsp salt
üíöKunafa Filling
* 260g kunafa pastry (finely chopped)
* 2 tbsp unsalted butter (for toasting kunafa)
* 320g pistachio cream
üç´Chocolate Ganache
* 120g double cream
* 100g milk chocolate (chopped)

Instructions
1. Preheat the oven to 170¬∞C and line a baking pan with parchment paper.
2. Brown 113g of unsalted butter in a saucepan until golden, then set aside.
3. Melt the chopped chocolate in the microwave in short bursts until smooth, then stir in the browned butter and let cool slightly.
4. In a separate bowl, whisk the sugar and eggs until light and fluffy.
5. Add the chocolate butter mixture to the eggs and sugar, and whisk until fully combined.
6. Fold in the flour, cocoa powder, and salt until just incorporated.
7. Pour all of the brownie batter into the prepared pan, smooth the top, and bake for 22 minutes. Let cool completely in the pan.
8. In a pan over medium heat, melt 2 tbsp of butter. Add the finely chopped kunafa pastry and cook, stirring often, until golden and crisp. Let cool slightly.
9. Mix the toasted kunafa pastry with the pistachio cream until fully combined, then spread evenly over the cooled brownie.
10. Place the pan in the fridge for about 30 minutes to set.
11. For the ganache, place the double cream and chopped milk chocolate in a microwave-safe bowl. Heat in short bursts, stirring in between, until melted and glossy.
12. Pour the ganache over the pistachio-kunafa layer, spread evenly, and refrigerate, ideally overnight, or at least 1 hour before slicing.

Enjoy! ü§é
